				<h3>	<p><span class="caps">HSE</span> Will Ensure Consistent Administration of Long Term Illness Card Nationally</p></h3>
							<p>	<p>From the Office of the Ombudsman:</p>

	<p><i>The Ombudsman, Peter Tyndall, has today welcomed the steps taken by the Health Service Executive (<span class="caps">HSE</span>) to ensure that the Long Term Illness card scheme does not discriminate on the basis of where an applicant lives. The Ombudsman&rsquo;s report, &#8216;Local Rules for National Schemes &#8211; Inequities in the administration of the Long Term Illness Card Scheme&rsquo;, follows a refusal by the <span class="caps">HSE</span> to award a Long Term Illness Card (<span class="caps">LTI</span> card) to a boy diagnosed with Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (<span class="caps">ADHD</span>).  The <span class="caps">HSE</span> refused the <span class="caps">LTI</span> card on the grounds that the boy did not meet the medical criteria for eligibility.  In her complaint to the Ombudsman, the boy&rsquo;s mother, Ms Kelly (not her real name), contended that her son met the relevant medical criteria and she claimed that had he lived elsewhere in Ireland (he lives in Wexford), her son would have been awarded a <span class="caps">LTI</span> card.</i></p>

	<p>For more details please see the Ombudsman <a href="https://www.ombudsman.gov.ie/en/News/Media-Releases/2014-Media-Releases/HSE-changes-policy-following-Ombudsman-investigation.html">media release</a>.</p>

